Subject:    <a href="?t=95837886900046&r=1&w=2">Re: root'ed vs. relative domain names</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837692300014&r=1&w=2">ralph%ucbarpa () Berkeley</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198503">1985-03-15 15:32:54</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426380&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426380&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

I have been using the 'if not dots, then append the domain' approach
for awhile. One problem is if you want to have subdomains like
ralph@pearl.cs and ralph@cory.ee, then they won't have 'berkeley.edu'
appended. I think that having the trailing '.' is more general
and just as simple to understand as the single label approach. 
The second thing to note is that I am implementing this at the resolver
level. I'm just as likely to ask for NS records for 'arpa.' as 
address records for 'arpa' (mapped to 'arpa.berkeley.edu.').
I want to distinguish between this cases unambiguously.

